75,90]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {This is going to be a full repertoire for Black
after the moves 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6. With the move 2...Nc6, Black attempts to
play the Sveshnikov that can arise after 3.d4, although White can also choose
to play some different attempts such as the Rossolimo. In this particular
lesson, the rare 3rd move alternatives for White will be analyzed.} 3. Bc4 {
The main move from the rare options. It became popular lately especially on
faster time-controls and many strong players have played it.} (3. b4 $6 {
This gambit doesn't seem very good for White, but it has been played by some
strong players, especially in blitz and rapid games.} Nxb4 {The easiest
continuation for Black in my opinion.} (3... cxb4 $5 4. d4 e6 {According to the
computers, Black can also get a good position here since d7-d5 is coming next,
while 5.d5 is going to be met with 5...Qf6, so this line is a playable
alternative.}) 4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 ({There are many games after:} 5... d5 6.
exd5 Qxd5 7. Na3 $13 {Black won a pawn, but White has the quicker development,
so the position remains complex.}) 6. cxd4 e6 $1 {This is a better move with
which Black can fight for an advantage.} (6... g6 {This is also a playable
alternative, intending Bg7 next.} 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. O-O d6 $132 {1/2 (53) Carlsen,
M (2839) -Hakobyan,A (2616) Chess.com INT 2023}) 7. Bd3 (7. d5 $2 {This fails
due to Black's next move:} Qf6 $1 8. dxc6 Qxa1 9. Qb3 {White will try to trap
the queen on a1 but it's not easy to do so.} bxc6 10. e5 {Intending Bd3 and
then Bb2, but Black has a strong resource:} a5 $1 11. Bd3 a4 12. Qc2 {0-1 (55)
Yoo,C (2485) -Praggnanandhaa,R (2618) chess24.com INT 2021} Bb4+ 13. Nbd2 (13.
Ke2 a3 {[%cal Ga1b2] If White ever moves the bishop from c1, Black can reply
with Qb2, exchanging the queens where the game will be practically over for
White.}) 13... Rb8 14. O-O Qc3 $19) (7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Nf6 9. Bd3 (9. e5 $6
Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4 $17) 9... d6 {If Black played 9...d5, White can reply with
10.e5 and Black will need to decide where to go with the knight. 9...d6 is
slightly more passive but Black is a pawn up without much compensation for
White.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Rb1 a5 $15) 7... d5 $1 {This is better than giving a
check on b4 in this line since White can simply cover with Nbd2 in comparison
to the line with 7.Nc3.} 8. e5 (8. exd5 $6 exd5 9. O-O Bd6 $17 {[%cal Gg8e7]})
(8. O-O dxe4 9. Bxe4 Nf6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ne5 {White will try to recover the
pawn by capturing on c6, but Black has the bishop pair and the d5-outpost, so
Black is clearly better.} Bd6 $15) 8... Nb4 $1 {This is a very good resource
for Black! With this move, Black manages to exchange White's light-squared
bishop and also, it will be easier to develop the rest of the pieces since
Black has less space.} 9. O-O (9. Be2 $2 Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2] Nc2 is
unstoppable since 10.Na3 runs into 10...Qc3+, winning material.}) 9... Nxd3 10.
Qxd3 a6 {This is the most accurate in my opinion, preventing any Nb5 ideas.}
11. Nc3 Bd7 12. Bd2 Ne7 13. Rfb1 Rb8 $15 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gf8e7] Black is behind
in development a bit, but that will be solved soon and White can't do much
since Black's position is very solid.}) (3. a3 {Preparing b2-b4.} g6 (3... Nf6
$5 4. Nc3 e5 {This is another playable option for Black where it's unclear
what is the pawn on a3 doing.}) (3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qd8 $11 {This
continuation is also possible.}) 4. Bb5 (4. b4 $6 Bg7 5. c3 d5 $1 6. exd5 Qxd5
7. bxc5 e5 $15 {Trying to push e4 and White is clearly in danger.}) 4... Bg7 {
This position looks like an improved Rossolimo for Black since moving the pawn
to a3 didn't accomplish much while White spent a tempo for it.}) (3. h3 g6 ({
Another option is:} 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 d6 {when the game can continue with 5.d4,
entering a classical Sicilian where the pawn is on h3 and isn't very dangerous
