Nxf4 O-O $11) 11... O-O 12. Nf5 d5 13. Nce3 Rd8 14. Qf3 Bf8 $11 15. exd5 cxd5
16. Nxd5 Qb7 17. c4 Rb8 18. Nfe3 Be6 $44 {[%csl Rd3] Black has good control
over the position and can exchange the knights with Ne7 later on, when the
pawn on d3 will become vulnerable.}) 8... Be7 {It's important to start with
this move.} 9. Nd2 (9. Ng3 h5 $1 {This is why it is better to start with 8...
Be7 instead of 8...Nf6.}) 9... Nf6 10. f4 exf4 11. Nxf4 O-O 12. Qf3 (12. Qe1
Re8 {Placing the rook against White's queen.}) 12... d5 $5 {Black is not
obliged to play this pawn sacrifice, but it can be quite interesting.} 13. exd5
cxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Bb7 16. Qh5 Qc6 $44) (6. h4 e5 7. Qe2 d6 $132 {
There was a line analyzed earlier when Black played Ne7 and went Ng8 back in a
similar position, so now the knight is already on g8 which is good for Black.})
6... Ne7 (6... e5 7. c3 {[%cal Gd3d4] d3-d4 is coming quickly.}) (6... d6 7.
Nfd2 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4] White will play f4 next.}) 7. h4 $5 ({After:} 7. Nh4 {
Black can simply exchange the knights.} Ng6 8. Qh5 Nxh4 9. Qxh4 Be7 10. Qg4 O-O
11. Bf4 d6 12. e5 {This is an interesting sacrifice suggested by the engine.}
dxe5 13. Bh6 Bf6 14. Qg3 Kh8 15. Bg5 Bxg5 16. Qxg5 Ba6 17. Nd2 {White would
like to put pressure on the c5 and e5-pawns, but the engine provides an
interesting way to play for Black.} c4 $5 18. dxc4 c5 $11 {Black will activate
the bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal.}) (7. Ng5 {This move has been played a lot,
but I don't like it very much for White.} h6 8. Nh3 d5 9. Nc3 (9. c4 g6 {
With Bg7 next.}) (9. f4 Ba6 {Intending c5-c4.}) 9... g6 10. Na4 e5 11. f4 Bg7
$132) (7. Re1 e5 $1 (7... Ng6 8. h4 {This can be a bit unpleasant for Black.})
8. c3 Ng6 9. d4 d6 10. dxc5 (10. Be3 Be7 {Is similar.}) 10... dxc5 11. Be3 Be7
12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Nc4 Be6 14. b3 Bxc4 15. bxc4 Rab8 $11) (7. e5 Ng6 8. Re1 Be7
9. h4 (9. Nc3 O-O {Black has a pleasant position.}) 9... f6 $11) 7... e5 $1 (
7... h5 8. e5 f6 9. Re1 $14) (7... f6 $6 8. h5 e5 9. Nh2 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]
Black's position is very passive.}) (7... d6 8. h5 h6 9. e5 $1 dxe5 10. Nbd2 g5
11. Re1 Bg7 12. Nc4 $14 {Now f7-f6 will be too passive and White can follow up
with Be3-Bxc5.}) 8. h5 (8. c3 {The difference in this line with c3 is that
h2-h4 has already been played, so the g4-square has been weakened.} d6 9. d4
Bg4 $132) 8... d6 (8... Ng8 $5 {This may be possible to play, but 8...d6 is
better in my opinion.} 9. b4 $5 $146 (9. Nh2 Nf6 10. f4 Be7 11. Ng4 $5 (11. Nc3
h6 $1 (11... d6 {1-0 (54) Caruana,F (2835) -Carlsen,M (2863) Lichess.org INT
2020} 12. Qf3 $14) 12. Qf3 O-O 13. Ng4 c4 $1 {Creating counterplay in the
position.} 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. dxc4 Ba6 $44) (11. h6 Rg8 $13) 11... Nxh5 (11...
c4 $5 {With a sharp position.}) 12. fxe5 d5 13. exd5 Bxg4 14. Qxg4 Qxe5 $13)
9... cxb4 10. d4 (10. a3 {Is similar and can lead to the same thing.}) 10... d6
11. a3 Nf6 12. axb4 h6 13. Na3 $14) (8... h6 9. Nh4 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 9. Nh2
(9. Nh4 Rg8 $1 {Anticipating White's f2-f4 idea and intending g7-g5.} 10. f4
exf4 11. Bxf4 g5 $1 12. hxg6 Nxg6 13. Nxg6 Rxg6 14. Na3 Be6 15. Nc4 O-O-O $11)
9... h6 $1 10. f4 (10. Qe2 g5 $1 11. g4 Bg7 $13 {[%cal Ge7g8,Gg8f6,Gf6h7,Gh7f8,
Gf8e6] The knight would stand best on the e6-square, being one jump away from
f4 or d4, so it's important for Black to reroute the knight with
Ng8-Nf6-Nh7-Nf8-Ne6. This plan may seem a bit slow, but White doesn't have any
active play that can put Black in immediate danger.}) 10... exf4 11. Bxf4 g5 $1
12. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3]} (12. Bg3 $5 f5 $5 $146 (12... Bg7 13. Nd2 {1/2-1/2 (48)
Grischuk,A (2736) -Rapport,R (2752) Dubai 2023}) 13. exf5 Nxf5 14. Nd2 Nxg3 15.
Qe1+ Kd8 16. Qxg3 d5 {With the king in the center, Black is going for the
endgame.} 17. Qxc7+ Kxc7 18. Rf7+ Bd7 19. Ng4 Re8 {White has some temporary
activity but Black's position is quite solid.} 20. Nf3 Re7 21. Rxe7 Bxe7 22.
Nfe5 Be8 23. Ng6 Rh7 24. Rf1 Rg7 $11) (12. hxg6 $6 Nxg6 13. Bd2 Rg8 $15 {
The g-file is open against White's king and Black is better.}) 12... Bg7 13.
Bc3 O-O 14. Bxg7 (14. Ng4 Bxg4 15. Qxg4 f5 16. exf5 Nd5 17. Bxg7 Qxg7 {Now
White should be careful since Black has threats such as Qxb2 and Ne3, so
White's best move is:} 18. f6 Rxf6 19. Rxf6 Qxf6 20. Nc3 $11) 14... Kxg7 15.
Qd2 {White is keeping the option of Qc3+ open.} (15. Nc3 Be6 16. Qd2 {
Transposes to 15.Qd2.}) 15... Be6 16. Qc3+ (16. Nc3 Rae8 {Black's position is
very solid, and the plan is to push f7-f5 eventually.} 17. Rf2 Qa5 $5 {[%cal
