) 18... Qd7 $1 {Black simply keeps everything defended well.} (18... f4 $2 19.
e5 d5 {1/2 (34) Aronian,L (2781) -Radjabov,T (2765) chess24.com INT 2021} 20.
Nb3 $16) 19. exf5 (19. Qa5 Rae8 20. e5 dxe5 21. Nhf3 (21. Qxc5 e4 $1 {Using
that the d-pawn is pinned at the moment.}) 21... e4 22. dxe4 g4 23. Ne5 Qd4+
24. Kh1 fxe4 {1/2 (24) Mena Corrochano,A (2107) -Reichgeld,M (2174) ICCF email
2021} (24... Qxe5 {It's logical to capture the knight on e5, and after:} 25.
exf5 Qg7 26. fxe6 Nf5 27. Qa3 {Black must play:} Qd4 $1 {which is not very
easy to find. So it's better to continue with 24...fxe4.} 28. Ne4 Rxe6 29. Rf4
Kh8 $13) 25. Rxf8 Rxf8 26. Rxe4 Qf2 27. Nxg4 Bxg4 28. Rxe7+ Kg8 29. Qxa7 Qh4+
30. Kg1 Qf2+ $11) (19. Nc4 f4 $1 {This is different from the Aronian -
Radjabov game above because now, Black's counterplay is sufficient.} 20. e5 d5
21. Nd6 g4 $1 22. Qxc5 f3 23. Re3 (23. gxf3 $2 g3 $17) 23... Rg8 24. d4 Nf5
$132) (19. Nhf3 Rae8 20. d4 c4 $1 21. Nh2 (21. Nxc4 $6 Bxc4 22. Qxc4 fxe4 {
[%cal Gd6d5] Black will play d5 next with a better position.}) 21... Bf7 $11)
19... Bxf5 20. Qc4 (20. Ne4 Nd5 21. Qd2 Rae8 $11) 20... Nd5 21. b4 {A very
good practical try from White.} (21. g4 $2 Nb6 $1 {A very strong in between
