{[%evp 0,34,19,28,70,70,60,32,53,53,41,18,15,24,16,19,9,21,10,17,11,7,6,-1,-7,
1,2,6,5,5,47,60,42,4,-4,-6,-12]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5.
b3 (5. c4 Ng6 {The arising positions can be quite similar to 4.c4.} ({Another
interesting option is:} 5... e5 $5) 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 {Black also has
other options to choose from:} (7... Be7 8. Nc3 O-O $11) (7... Qc7 8. Nc3 Bd6
$11) 8. Ba4 Bc5 $5 9. Be3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Qg5 11. Bxc5 (11. g3 b5 $132) 11...
Qxc5 12. Nc3 O-O $11 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gg6e5] This position was discussed in
the previous lesson under the move 4.c4.}) (5. Ba4 a6 6. c4 (6. c3 {Transposes
to 5.c3 that is analyzed in the next lesson.}) 6... Ng6 7. Nc3 (7. d4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 {Transposes to 5.c4.}) 7... Nd4 $5 {Other normal moves such as 7...Be7
are also possible of course, although this knight jump seems quite tempting to
play.} 8. d3 b5 $1 {Sacrificng a pawn for the initiative.} 9. cxb5 axb5 10.
Bxb5 {10.Nxb5 can be met with 10...Nxf3, when White will have to recapture
with the g-pawn which will damage White's kingside pawn structure.} (10. Nxd4
bxa4 11. Ndb5 Be7 12. Nxa4 O-O 13. Nac3 f5 $132 {An important move, trying to
open up the h1-a8 diagonal for the bishop and the f-file for the rook. Black
has a very nice initiative.}) 10... Nxb5 11. Nxb5 Ba6 12. Nc3 (12. Na3 Be7 13.
Nc4 O-O 14. Re1 f5 15. e5 Bb7 $44 {The bishop is very well placed on the h1-a8
diagonal.}) 12... Be7 13. Re1 O-O 14. d4 f5 $44 {Black is the one fighting for
an advantage}) (5. Nc3 a6 {Forcing White to make a decision with the bishop.} (
5... Nd4 {Trying to transpose to a line analyzed in the previous lesson, but
White is not forced to oblige.} 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 a6 8. Bd3 Nc6 {With a
playable position for Black.}) (5... Ng6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Be7 {Is another
option that Black can try.}) 6. Bxc6 (6. Be2 Nd4 $11 {Once White has played
Be2, this knight jump is even better for Black because after capturing the
knight with Nxd4, White can't retreat with Ne2 anymore.}) 6... Nxc6 7. d4 (7.
Re1 Be7 {Other options for Black include:} (7... b5) (7... Qc7) 8. d4 cxd4 9.
Nxd4 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5 f6 {A typical move.} 12. exf6 Bxf6 {I prefer to
keep the dark-squared bishop on the board in order to have better control over
the dark squares.} (12... Rxf6 $5 13. Bg5 Rg6 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11 {Black can
start pushing the central pawns forward with e6-e5 and d7-d5.}) 13. Ne4 Be5 14.
Nd6 {This is basically a draw offer.} (14. Qh5 Bb8 15. Bg5 Qe8 16. Qxe8 Rxe8
17. c4 d5 18. Nc5 Bd6 19. Nd3 e5 20. Bf4 Bf5 21. Nxe5 dxc4 $11) (14. c4 d5 15.
Ng5 Bf6 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Rxe6 dxc4 18. Qe2 {The doubled c-pawns are weak but
the strong bishop on f6 compensates for them.} Qd3 19. Qxd3 cxd3 20. Rxc6 Rfc8
21. Rxc8+ Rxc8 $11) 14... Bxh2+ (14... Qh4 15. g3 {White managed to defend
against Black's immediate threats.}) 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Qxf2+ $11) 7... cxd4
8. Nxd4 Nxd4 $5 {This is a rarer option and can be quite interesting.} ({
The most popular move is} 8... Qc7) 9. Qxd4 b5 {Black wants to develop the
bishop to b7 as soon as possible.} 10. Rd1 (10. Bf4 Bb7 11. Rad1 f6 $1 {
This is a typical move in this pawn structure because there is pressure on the
g7-pawn and it's difficult to develop the bishop from f8. Now Black is
threatening e6-e5 and if that is prevented, Black intends to continue with Rc8,
Bc5, and to castle after that.} 12. Qd3 (12. Bd6 Bxd6 13. Qxd6 Bc6 $11 {
[%cal Gd8e7]}) 12... Rc8 13. a3 Bc5 14. Rfe1 O-O {Black can sacrifice the
d7-pawn although it's not necessary to do so.} 15. Qxd7 (15. Bd6 Rf7 16. Bxc5
Rxc5 $11) 15... Qxd7 16. Rxd7 Rf7 17. Rd3 (17. Rxf7 Kxf7 18. Rd1 Ke7 $44 {
Black is threatening Bxa3 or b5-b4.}) 17... b4 18. axb4 Bxb4 $11 {Even though
Black is a pawn down, the position has a drawing tendency because the bishop
pair is strong.}) (10. Be3 Bb7 11. Rad1 f6 12. Rfe1 Rc8 $11 {[%cal Gf8c5]})
10... Bb7 11. Be3 (11. a4 b4 12. Ne2 Rc8 $5 {I prefer this move, although 12...
d5 is also playable.} (12... d5 13. e5 Qc7 14. Be3 a5 15. Qf4 Be7 16. Nd4 O-O
17. Qg3 Kh8 $11 {The position may be a bit passive for Black, but on the other
hand, Black will always have pressure on White's c-pawn thanks to the pawn on
b4.}) 13. c3 bxc3 14. Nxc3 f6 $132 {Intending Bc5 next.}) 11... Bc6 $5 ({
Another playable option is:} 11... f6 12. a4 b4 13. Ne2 Bc6 14. Qd3 Be7 15. Nd4
Bb7 16. Nb3 Rc8 $13) 12. Ne2 Qb8 (12... Qf6 $5 {The endgame is fine for Black
according to the engines.}) 13. a3 f6 14. Qd3 Qb7 15. f3 Kf7 16. Nd4 Be7 17.
Nxc6 dxc6 18. Qd7 Qxd7 19. Rxd7 Rhd8 20. Rc7 Rdc8 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 $11) 5... a6 6.
Bxc6 Nxc6 7. d4 {It's better to start with 7.d4 instead of 7.Bb2.} (7. Bb2 b5 {
Transposes to the previous lessons.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qc7 (8... Qf6 $6 {
This idea doesn't work in this position because White's bishop is not on b2
yet, so White has:} 9. Be3 Bc5 $2 10. Nxc6 Bxe3 11. e5 Qg5 12. fxe3 Qxe3+ 13.
Kh1 bxc6 14. Qd6 $16) 9. Bb2 {With this move order, White managed to avoid the
Qf6 idea but Black is fine anyway after:} Bd6 10. Nxc6 (10. Qh5 Nxd4 11. Bxd4
O-O 12. Bxg7 {Leads to a perpetual check.} (12. c4 f5 13. Nc3 b6 $11 {[%cal
Gc8b7]}) 12... Kxg7 13. Qg5+ $11) 10... dxc6 11. Bxg7 Bxh2+ 12. Kh1 Rg8 13. Qh5
Rxg7 14. Qxh2 e5 ({Also good is:} 14... Qxh2+ 15. Kxh2 e5 $11) 15. Nc3 Bd7 {
[%cal Ge8c8] Black wants to castle long and bring the a8-rook into the action
with Rdg8.} 16. Qh4 {[%cal Gh4d8] White should prevent Black from castling,
otherwise White risks falling in an inferior position.} Qd8 17. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $11 *

