{[%evp 0,46,22,13,51,46,46,29,29,25,46,46,46,46,43,17,-15,0,1,-22,-8,-1,-8,-9,
8,16,19,6,19,3,12,-27,3,-31,-10,-25,4,-6,4,0,0,3,6,20,13,6,16,20,13]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9.
Nab1 {A rare, but decent line. The idea is to put the first knight on d5 and
bring the other one to c3.} Be7 {Black should be able to achieve a very good
position with simple moves.} ({Other options are:} 9... Be6) ({and} 9... Ne7)
10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. a4 ({White can start playing without a4 with} 11. Nd5 O-O {
, but it should most probably transpose anyway. Omitting a4 altogether is
nothing Black should worry about.}) 11... b4 ({Also possible is} 11... Nd4 12.
Bd3 (12. axb5 Bg4 13. Be2 Nxe2 14. Nxe2 axb5 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. h3 Be6 17. Qxd6
Qxe4 18. Qb8+ Bd8 19. Nbc3 Qc6 20. Qxe5 O-O 21. O-O Bf6 $11) 12... b4 13. Nd5
Rb8 14. Nd2 O-O 15. O-O a5 $11) 12. Nd5 O-O ({Similar is} 12... Be6) 13. Bc4 (
13. Nd2 Be6 {is similar. White will probably put the bishop on c4 anyway.}) (
13. c3 Rb8) 13... Be6 ({Also good is} 13... Bg5) 14. O-O ({After other moves
we play ...Bg5 and the game is likely to transpose:} 14. Nd2 Bg5) ({or} 14. Qd3
Bg5) 14... Bg5 15. Qd3 (15. c3 a5 16. Qd3 {Transpose to 15.Qd3.}) (15. Nd2 Kh8
{Stepping out of the a2-g8 diagonal to prepare ...f5.} 16. Nf3 Bh6 17. Qd3 (17.
Qe2 f5 {There is a forcing sequence possible:} 18. Nxb4 fxe4 19. Nxc6 exf3 20.
Nxd8 fxe2 21. Nxe6 exf1=Q+ 22. Kxf1 Rfc8 23. b3 Rab8 24. Rd1 Rc6 $132 {[%csl
Re6] Black is fine with the e6-knight lacking squares to go to.}) 17... f5 18.
Ne3 Bxc4 ({Also good is} 18... fxe4 19. Qxe4 Bxc4 20. Qxc4 Rc8 21. Qxa6 e4 22.
Nd2 d5 $44 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]}) 19. Qxc4 fxe4 20. Qxe4 Bxe3 21. fxe3 (21. Qxc6 Bc5
{[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc5f2] The bishop is very strong. White should be careful.}) (
21. Qxe3 h6 22. Rad1 Qc7 $11) 21... d5 22. Qg4 Qe7 $11 {Our pawns are extended,
but we can easily defend them.}) 15... a5 16. c3 (16. Nd2 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Nd4 18.
Qd3 Rc8 $11) (16. Rd1 Rc8) 16... Rc8 17. Rd1 (17. Ba6 bxc3 18. bxc3 Rb8 19. Bb5
Ne7 $11) (17. Nd2 {We can initiate direct tactics to equalize by force:} bxc3
18. bxc3 Bxd2 19. Qxd2 Nd4 {The point.} 20. Qd3 Bxd5 21. exd5 (21. Bxd5 $2 Rxc3
$1) 21... Qc7 22. cxd4 Qxc4 23. Qxc4 Rxc4 24. dxe5 dxe5 $11) 17... bxc3 18.
Nbxc3 (18. bxc3 Ne7 $11 {A simple idea. If the knight comes out of b1, Black
can simply trade everything on d5 and capture on c3.}) 18... Nb4 $1 {Black
takes advantage of the newly created outpost.} 19. Qe2 h5 $5 {An interesting
kingside expansion that can prove useful in the long run. The position has a
non-forcing character now and Black has enough time for such moves.} (19... Rc5
{is a simple and good alternative. The character of the position doesn't
change.} 20. b3 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 g6 22. Rd3 Kg7 $11) 20. b3 (20. h3 g6 21. b3 Nxd5
22. Nxd5 Rc5 23. Rd3 Kg7 24. Rad1 Qb8 $11 {0-1 (42) Lavrencic,M (2350) -Yaniv,Y
(2390) Iasi 2023}) 20... Nxd5 ({It is also worth considering to provoke a
slight kingside weakening:} 20... Bg4 $5 21. f3 Be6) 21. Nxd5 g6 22. Ra2 (22.
Rd3 Kg7 23. Rad1 Rc5 $11) 22... Bg4 {The same idea as in the alternative 20...
Bg4 line.} 23. f3 Be6 $11 {1/2 (31) Colbow, C (2379) -Sebastian, D (2435)
Germany 2023 It is not easy for Black to become better in these positions, but
on the other hand, he is very solid and doesn't run many risks.} *

