13. Bxe4 Bg7 (13... Rc8 {Also possible}) 14. Qh5 (14. O-O O-O 15. c3 f5 16. Bg2
Rb8 17. Nc2 a5 {With the typical double idea of stopping Nb4 and preparing ...
b4.} 18. a3 (18. Qe2 Kh8 19. Rad1 b4 {If White doesn't prevent this advance,
Black should be happy to play it.} 20. c4 b3 21. axb3 Rxb3 $132) 18... Kh8 ({
Also good is} 18... Qd7) ({Or} 18... Ne7) 19. Qh5 Ne7 20. Nce3 Ng8 $5 {This is
an unusual engine idea. Black avoids the knight exchange to put the e3-knight
under attack with ...f4.} (20... Nxd5 {is more straightforward and also good.}
21. Nxd5 e4 22. Rad1 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gg7e5]}) 21. Rae1 (21. f4 e4 {Now Black
gets a protected passed pawn.}) 21... f4 22. Be4 Nh6 {The point.} 23. Ng2 Bg4
24. Qh4 Qxh4 25. Nxh4 Nf7 $132 {[%cal Gf7g5] Very original play. The ...Ng5
resource guarantees Black a good game.}) (14. Nf6+ Bxf6 15. Bxc6+ Ke7 16. c3 (
16. Bxa8 $2 Qxa8 $17 {Grabbing the exchange is quite obviously not recommended
for White. The weak light squares are looming.}) 16... Rc8 17. Bd5 (17. Bg2 $2
b4 $1 {Black takes over the initiative by means of a tactical pawn sacrifice.}
18. cxb4 e4 {[%cal Gf6b2]} 19. Qe2 d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]} 20. O-O Qb6 $17 {
With big problems for White.}) 17... b4 $5 $146 {Dynamic play looks more
convincing than static play here, although both ways are fine.} (17... Rc5 18.
Bxe6 fxe6 19. Nc2 {1/2 (29) Almasi, Z (2682) -Gledura, B (2622) /Hungary HUN
2019/ The Week in Chess 1269 (29)} h5 $11 {=+}) 18. cxb4 Qb6 19. O-O Qxb4 20.
