19. Qe3 f5 (19... h5 $5) 20. Bg2 e4 21. Nac2 (21. O-O Kf7) 21... a5 22. Nd4 Bc4
23. Nbc2 {1/2 (59) Nikitenko,M (2408) -Moiseenko,A (2648) /Skopje MKD 2019/The
Week in Chess 1271 (59) Black could have achieved some advantage with} b4 24.
cxb4 axb4 25. b3 Bf7 26. O-O d5 $15) 17... Qxe7 18. Nc2 (18. O-O h6 {[%cal
Gd6d5,Ge8g8] With ...d5 and ...0-0 ideas, but also possibly ...Qg5.} 19. Rd2 d5
20. Bg2 (20. Bf5 $6 Qg5 $1 $15) 20... e4 21. Qe2 h5 $5 22. Nc2 h4 23. Rfd1 Qg5
$132) 18... d5 19. Bf5 d4 20. O-O Bxf5 21. Qxf5 O-O (21... dxc3 22. bxc3 e4 $11
) 22. cxd4 exd4 {With the d4-pawn protected by the bishop, Black's position is
extremely solid.} 23. Qd3 Qe6 24. a3 Qa2 25. Rb1 Qc4 26. Ne1 f5 27. Rd1 f4 $11
{1/2 (39) Meissen,F (2431) -Pohjosmaeki,R (2330) ICCF email 2021}) (15. Rd1 Ne7
{Will transpose}) 15... Ne7 16. Nxe7 (16. Rad1 Nxd5 (16... Rc5 {This natural
move runs into a very interesting idea for White:} 17. Nxe7 Qxe7 18. b4 Rc7 19.
c4 {White sacrifices a pawn to dominate the light squares.} bxc4 20. Nc2 {
[%cal Gc2e3]} h6 21. Ne3 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5]} O-O 22. Nd5 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 $14) 17.
Bxd5 O-O 18. c3 (18. Qe2 Rc5 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. c4 d5 21. cxb5 (21. cxd5 exd5
22. Nc2 Qd6 $11) 21... Qb6 $1 22. Rc1 (22. bxa6 $6 e4 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2][%cal
Gg7b2]}) 22... Rxc1 23. Rxc1 e4 24. Rc6 Qb7 {1/2 (28) Ortiz Hernandez,R (2313)
