{[%evp 0,48,22,13,46,46,46,25,31,6,31,28,43,56,35,9,9,-9,18,-12,16,22,7,-33,
-43,-50,-68,-72,-66,-66,-66,-66,89,83,83,72,166,179,35,67,67,44,41,55,55,55,46,
46,49,49,87]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6
7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 f5 11. Bxb5 {Back in the day this
sacrifice was a big one. Nowadays almost nobody plays it because Black has
plenty of ways to equalize.} (11. Nxb5 $2 {This is just a bad idea.} axb5 12.
Bxb5 Bb7 {Compared to the lines with the Nxb5 sacrifice after 11.c3, the
bishop gets to the active long diagonal. White's compensation is questionable.}
13. exf5 Rc8 14. O-O Bg7 15. Qf3 (15. c3 O-O $17) 15... Bf6 16. c3 Kf8 $17)
11... axb5 12. Nxb5 Ra4 {The main move} ({There are also other good options:}
12... Ra5) ({and} 12... Bb7) 13. Nbc7+ (13. O-O $6 {A dubious choice.} Be7 $1 {
The king can hide on f8 after a check now.} 14. b4 Nxb4 15. c4 Nxd5 16. Qxa4
Nf4 {A discovered check is not devastating by any means here.} 17. Nxd6+ Kf8
18. Nxf5 Rg8 19. g3 Ne2+ 20. Kg2 Nd4 $15 {White only fights for survival.}) (
13. c4 $2 {This simply doesn't work.} Rxc4 14. Nbc7+ (14. O-O Be7 15. Rc1 Rc5
$19) 14... Kd7 15. O-O (15. Qh5 Rxe4+ 16. Kf1 Qh4 17. Qxf7+ Be7 $19 {
Everything is covered and White is just a piece down.}) 15... Nd4 $1 16. Nb6+
Kxc7 17. Nxc4 Kb8 $19 {The minor pieces are much, much stronger than the rook
here, especially considering the ...Bb7, ...Rg8 idea. Black is winning.}) (13.
b4 $5 {An additional pawn sacrifice played to open the b-file that might be
useful in some lines.} Rxb4 ({Also good is} 13... Qh4 $5 14. O-O Rg8) 14. Nbc7+
Kd7 15. O-O Rg8 {Many other good options} 16. Rb1 $1 fxe4 {The most practical
continuation, which puts an onus on White to find a narrow path to a draw.} (
16... Rxe4 17. Qf3 $1 Qg5 (17... Nd4 $6 18. Qa3) 18. g3 Be7 19. Qc3 Bd8 20.
Nb6+ Kxc7 21. Nxc8 Rg6 $132) 17. c3 $1 (17. Nxb4 $6 Nxb4 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5
Ke7 $15 {Black is just better with the two bishops.}) 17... Rxb1 18. Qxb1 Qh4
19. g3 Qh3 20. Qb5 Rg6 {[%cal Gg6h6]} 21. f4 {The only move!} Rxg3+ $11 {
With a perpetual.}) 13... Kd7 14. O-O (14. b4 $6 Qh4 15. O-O Rg8 16. f4 Kd8 17.
c3 Ra7 $15) 14... Rxe4 (14... Rg8 {Also good}) 15. Qh5 Qh4 $5 {A rare, but
fully satisfactory move.} ({More popular is} 15... Nd4) 16. Qxf7+ (16. Qxf5+ $2
Kd8 17. Qxf7 Be7 18. g3 Rg4 $17) 16... Be7 {There are quite a few options
possible for White here. A lot of Black moves in the following lines should be
perfectly possible to find over the board. One crucial idea worth remembering
is meeting g3 with ...Rg4!} 17. Nxe7 (17. g3 Rg4 18. Ne6 Nb4 $5 19. Nb6+ Kc6
20. Nxc8 Rxc8 21. Nd4+ $1 exd4 22. Qc4+ Kd7 23. Qxb4 Qf6 24. Rfe1 h5 25. Qb5+
Kd8 26. Qb6+ $11) (17. Nb5 Kd8 $5 18. Nxe7 Qxe7 19. Qd5 Kd7 20. Rad1 Nd4 21. f3
Ne2+ 22. Kh1 Rh4 23. Qxd6+ Qxd6 24. Rxd6+ Ke7 25. Re1 Rb4 26. Rd5 Nf4 27.
Rdxe5+ Kf6 28. b3 Rd8 $132 29. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nd3) (17. Ne6 Nd8 $1 18. Nxd8
Kxd8 19. g3 Rg4 20. Nb6 Qf6 (20... Bb7 21. Rad1 Qh6 22. Qxf5 Rxg3+ 23. fxg3
Qe3+ 24. Rf2 Qxb6 25. Qxe5 Rf8 26. Rd4 $11) 21. Qd5 Qe6 22. Qa8 f4 23. Rad1
fxg3 24. fxg3 Rf8 25. Rxf8+ Bxf8 $132) 17... Nxe7 18. Nd5 Kd8 19. g3 (19. Nf6
Qh6 20. Nxe4 fxe4 $132) 19... Rg4 20. Nf6 Qh6 21. Nxg4 fxg4 22. Rad1 Nc6 23. f4
(23. Qd5 Kc7) (23. f3 Rf8 24. Qd5 Kc7 $132 {[%cal Gh6e3]}) 23... Rf8 24. Qd5
Kc7 $132 {According to the engine the position is equal. In practice White
should be careful with a pretty exposed king and Black's bishop ready to
appear on the long diagonal.} *

