f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Bd3 (12. Qf3 $2 Nd4 13. Nc7+ (13. Nf6+ Ke7 $19) 13... Qxc7
14. Qxa8+ Ke7 $19 {Black has all the activity and ...Bh6 is coming.}) (12. Be2
Nd4 $5 {A great concrete solution.} ({Normal is} 12... Bg7 13. O-O O-O 14. c3
Rb8) 13. c3 Be4 14. cxd4 (14. Ne3 Nxe2 15. Qxe2 Rg8 16. Nac2 Bh6 17. O-O Qd7
18. f3 Bb7 $132 {The bishops are menacing.}) 14... Bxd5 15. O-O Bg7 16. Bf3
Bxf3 17. Qxf3 O-O $11) (12. c3 Bg7 {Transpose to the next lessons.}) 12... Be6
13. Be4 {This is the same position as in the 11.g3 line, but with the pawn
back on g2. This fact makes it even more comfortable for Black.} Bg7 ({SImilar
is} 13... Rc8) 14. Qh5 (14. Nf6+ $6 {A dubious choice.} Bxf6 15. Bxc6+ Ke7 16.
O-O (16. Bxa8 $2 Qxa8 17. O-O b4 18. Nb1 Bh3 {It turns out the position of the
pawn in fact makes it easier for Black to create a decisive attack!} 19. f3 Rg8
20. g3 Qa7+ 21. Rf2 Bg5 $19) 16... Rc8 17. Bd5 b4 18. Nb1 Rg8 $132 {White
should be very careful.}) 14... Rc8 15. O-O (15. Rd1 Ne7 {will likely
transpose.}) 15... Ne7 16. Rad1 Rc5 (16... Nxd5 17. Bxd5 O-O $11 {Also good.})
17. Nb4 (17. Nxe7 Qxe7 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black is ready to push ...d5.}) 17...
Qb6 18. Nd3 Rc7 19. Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d5]} a5 $5 {It is essentially White who
fights to equalize now.} ({We can also make a draw with} 19... Rc5 $11) 20. Nd5
Bxd5 21. Bxd5 O-O 22. c4 Rc5 23. Qf3 Nxd5 24. Rxd5 bxc4 25. Qe3 $1 {White
equalizes.} Rb8 (25... c3 $11) 26. Rxc5 Qxc5 27. Qxc5 dxc5 28. Nxc4 a4 $11 {
[%cal Ge5e4] White will not be able to block our bishop.} *

