Qh3+ 28. Ke2 Qxg4+ 29. Qxg4 Bxg4+ 30. Kd2 Rxe7 $11) 21... Qa1+ 22. Qd1 (22. Ke2
$6 Qb1 $17) 22... Qxb2 {We could play 22...Qa5+ back with a draw, but it is
already White who has to be more careful here, so why not continue playing?}
23. Bd3 Bxf5 24. Bxf5 Qc3+ 25. Ke2 (25. Kf1 Re8 {[%csl Re7]}) 25... Re8 26. Re1
Rxe7+ 27. Kf1 $11 {This is objectively a draw, but we are still two pawns up
and can consider playing for a win.}) 18... Qa2 19. Nxe6 (19. cxd4 exd4 $15)
19... Nxe6 20. Bd3 (20. Bxb5 Qxb2) 20... Qxb2 21. O-O Rd8 22. Nd5 (22. Qh5 h6)
22... Nf4 23. Nxf4 exf4 24. Qg4 Qxc3 25. Qh4 Rb8 26. Bxh7+ Kf8 27. Qxf4 $11) (
14. Bd3 Be6 15. Qh5 f5 16. Nce3 {Transpose to 14.Nce3.}) 14... Be6 15. Bd3 (15.
g4 Ne7 (15... b4 $5 16. Bg2 bxc3 17. bxc3 Rc8) 16. Bg2 Rc8 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18.
Qd3 Kh8 $11 {[%cal Gb5b4] It's hard for White to castle with g4 played. The ...
b4 break is our main plan.}) (15. g3 f5 16. Bg2 f4 17. Nc2 (17. gxf4 exf4 18.
Nxf4 Rxf4 19. Bxc6 Qh4 $132 {This is certainly risky for White, despite him
being a pawn up.}) 17... Bf5 18. gxf4 exf4 19. Nxf4 Bxc2 20. Qxc2 Rxf4 21. Bxc6
Rc8 22. Bd5+ Kh8 23. Rg1 b4 $11 {Again, a temporary pawn advantage for White,
but an initiative for Black.}) (15. Qh5 f5 16. Bd3 {Transpose to 15.Bd3.}) (15.
a4 b4 $132) 15... f5 16. O-O (16. Bc2 f4 {There are also other good options.}
17. Qh5 Rf7 $1 {This leads to a very well-known forced draw:} 18. Bxh7+ Kf8 19.
Bf5 Qe8 20. Bxe6 Qxe6 21. Qg4 Qh6 22. Nf5 (22. O-O e4 23. Nf5 Qe6 24. Nfe3 Qh6
$11) 22... Qe6 23. Nfe3 Qh6 $11) (16. Qh5 e4 17. Bc2 Ne7 18. Rd1 (18. Nf4 Bf7
19. Bb3 (19. Qh3 $6 Kh8 $15 {[%cal Gg7e5] Black is already becoming better.})
19... d5 $132) 18... b4 $5 {The typical break played in order to achieve more
files and diagonals for our pieces.} (18... Kh8 {Also fine}) 19. cxb4 (19. Nxb4
a5 20. Nbd5 Rb8 $132 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 21. Bb3 f4) (19. Bb3 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21.
Nxd5 bxc3 22. bxc3 Qe8 23. Qxe8 Raxe8 24. O-O $11) (19. O-O bxc3 20. bxc3 Kh8
$11) 19... Rc8 (19... Ng6 $5) 20. Bb3 Ng6 21. g3 (21. O-O Kh8 {[%cal Gf5f4]}
22. g3 f4 23. Nxf4 Nxf4 24. gxf4 Bxb3 25. axb3 Rxf4 $11) 21... Kh8 22. Nf4 Nxf4
23. gxf4 Bxb3 24. axb3 Qf6 25. Nd5 (25. O-O Qh6 26. Qxh6 Bxh6 {[%cal Gh6f4]}
27. Rxd6 Bxf4 28. Rxa6 Bxe3 29. fxe3 Rc2 $11) 25... Qxb2 26. O-O Rb8 27. Kh1 (
27. Rfe1 Bd4 $11) 27... Rb7 28. Ne3 Bd4 $11) (16. a4 b4 17. O-O bxc3 18. bxc3
Kh8 $132) 16... Kh8 $5 ({Other options are} 16... Ra7) (16... e4) 17. Qh5 (17.
Bc2 Ne7 $132) (17. a4 b4 $1 {A strong reaction to a4.} 18. cxb4 e4 19. Nf4 Nd4
20. Nxe6 Nxe6 21. Bc4 Nd4 $132 {Black has a promising compensation for the
pawn. As usual in opposite-colored bishops' position, the activity can easily
prove more important than material.}) 17... e4 {We carry out the thematic pawn
advance.} 18. Bc2 Ne7 19. Rad1 (19. Nf4 Bf7 20. Qg5 (20. Qh3 $6 Be5 $15) 20...
d5 $5 {Black can give up a pawn like that to open one more file for his major
pieces.} (20... Be5) 21. Nxf5 Nxf5 22. Qxf5 Bg8 23. Qg4 Bh6 24. Ne2 Qf6 $132 {
Black's compensation is pretty self-explanatory.}) (19. Nxe7 $6 Qxe7 20. Rad1
Rae8 21. Nd5 Qa7 22. Bb3 Be5 $15 {[%cal Gf5f4]}) 19... Bf7 {Pushing the queen
out of its ideal h5-square.} ({Other decent options are:} 19... b4) (19... Rc8)
20. Qh3 (20. Qe2 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5] Planning to target the
central knight with ...Rc5.} 22. f3 Bh5 $132 {A good rebuttal to f2-f3.}) (20.
