-6,-17,-15,5,16,9,-10,-17]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 {In this lesson we
see a few minor lines.} 11. g3 (11. Nxf6+ $6 {It's obviously a dubious choice
to give up this knight for this bishop.} Qxf6 12. Bd3 (12. c3 Ne7 13. Bd3 Qg5
14. g3 (14. O-O Ng6 $15 {[%cal Gg6f4]}) 14... O-O $132) 12... Nd8 $5 $146 {
[%cal Gd8e6] A really nice maneuver. The knight quickly gets access to f4,
from where it threatens White's king.} (12... O-O 13. O-O Be6 $11 {This is a
more standard continuation with an easy equality.}) 13. O-O Ne6 $132 {[%cal
Ge6f4]}) (11. Bd3 Bg5 12. O-O O-O 13. c3 Ne7 $11) (11. Be2 O-O 12. c3 Bg5 {
Will transpose to the next lessons.}) 11... O-O 12. Bg2 Bg5 13. O-O Be6 {
[%cal Gc6e7]} 14. Qd3 (14. c3 Ne7) 14... g6 $5 ({Many other good moves as well.
} 14... Ne7) ({or} 14... Rc8) 15. Rfd1 (15. c4 Nd4 {A typical pawn sacrifice.}
16. cxb5 Bxd5 17. exd5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Nxb5 19. Qxb5 Rb8 20. Qe2 Qa5 $132 {
Only White can be in danger in a position like this, due to his worse bishop
and worse structure. The one pawn advantage is not as relevant, as is often
the case in opposite-coloured bishops positions.}) 15... f5 $132 {Black is
doing great.} *

